Let's see: in the Java code, when found, i is the index (0-based), then it does ++i and returns. So the printed value is i+1. So in Fortran, the indices are 1-based, so just print i.

Wait, in Java, when it finds the index i (0-based), it does System.out.println(++i); which is i+1. So in Fortran, since the loop is 1-based, if found, print i. So for the loop part: In Java:

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    if (left == a.get(i) && right == b.get(i)) {
        System.out.println(++i);
        return;
    }
} So in Fortran:

do i = 1, n
    if (a(i) == left .and. b(i) == right) then
        print *, i
        stop
    end if
end do
print *, -1

Yes.
